          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be low price-sensitive \u2014 you rarely let price dictate your choices, prioritising value and quality over finding the cheapest option. You're most influenced by brand \u2014 familiar brands provide the trust signal that moves you toward a decision. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Wants control but is drawn to delegating decisions to others."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I still remember the contaminated batch incident \u2014 it changed everything about how I buy anything my family consumes. I don't cut corners on quality, period. Price barely registers for me; what I need is verified certifications, transparent ingredient lists, and a brand I've personally vetted over time. Once I find that brand, I stay. Switching isn't something I do casually.\n\nBut here's my honest tension: I want to research everything myself, cross-check every label, control every purchase decision \u2014 yet I constantly catch myself asking my close friends what they're using, almost craving someone I trust to just tell me it's safe. I'm drawn to brands my peer circle already believes in.\n\nI'll still verify it myself. I always do. But knowing someone I respect already trusts a brand? That moves me faster than any advertisement ever could.",
          "third_person": "Priya Sharma is a 34-year-old postgraduate professional navigating early motherhood in Mumbai while maintaining a demanding full-time career. Her decision-making is shaped profoundly by a past encounter with a contaminated product batch \u2014 an experience that permanently recalibrated her purchasing psychology toward rigorous quality verification. She now treats ingredient transparency and certified sourcing as non-negotiable prerequisites, not optional reassurances.\n\nPriya's analytical disposition means she rarely acts on impulse; she systematically evaluates information before committing. Yet this thoroughness coexists with a persistent tension: she desires control over household decisions but finds herself gravitating toward trusted peers for validation, revealing an underlying need for social confirmation before she finalizes choices. This dynamic explains why peer recommendations carry such disproportionate weight despite her self-directed research habits.\n\nHer very high brand loyalty is not blind allegiance \u2014 it is earned trust, maintained through consistent quality signals over time. Because price sensitivity is low, she will readily absorb premium costs to stay within brands she has already vetted. Switching carries psychological risk she considers unacceptable, making familiarity and reliability her ultimate purchasing currency.",
          "display_name": "Priya"
        },
        "decision_bullets": [
          "Decision style: analytical (score 0.30)",
          "Primary value driver: quality",
          "Risk appetite: medium",
          "Objection (medium likelihood, friction): need more information",
