          ],
          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by community \u2014 online reviews and community consensus are central to your decision process. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I still think about that laptop I bought in my second year of postgrad \u2014 the one that died three months in because I chose the cheaper option. Lost assignments, repair costs, the whole nightmare. That lesson stuck with me hard.\n\nNow I'm living alone in Chennai on a mid-level salary, and every significant purchase feels like a calculation. I want the good stuff \u2014 I genuinely believe quality pays for itself over time \u2014 but my budget doesn't always agree with my principles. So I spend hours on forums, Reddit threads, YouTube reviews, asking colleagues what they actually use and regret. I trust real people over brand promises.\n\nI'm not impulsive. I'll wait, compare, revisit. But once the community consensus aligns with the value I'm seeing, I commit. Cutting corners burned me once. I won't let it happen again.",
          "third_person": "Karthik Rajan is a 27-year-old postgraduate professional living alone in Chennai, navigating early career demands on a middle income. His consumer behavior is fundamentally shaped by a formative experience \u2014 a defective laptop purchase that taught him, concretely, that cheap often costs more over time. This single incident recalibrated his entire decision-making framework around quality as a non-negotiable primary value, even when his budget resists it.\n\nWhat makes Karthik analytically distinctive is the deliberate tension he manages rather than resolves. He does not impulsively chase quality, nor does he surrender to purely budget-driven choices. Instead, he systematically researches options, leaning heavily on peer reviews and online community consensus as his most trusted signal \u2014 essentially outsourcing risk assessment to collective experience rather than brand authority or advertising.\n\nHis switching behavior is measured and slow, reflecting a risk-averse temperament that demands sufficient evidence before committing. Price-to-value ratio is his central evaluative lens. He is essentially optimizing for long-term utility within short-term financial constraints, making him a cautious but ultimately quality-oriented consumer who distrusts shortcuts.",
          "display_name": "Karthik"
        },
        "decision_bullets": [
          "Decision style: analytical (score 0.30)",
          "Primary value driver: quality",
          "Risk appetite: medium",
          "Objection (high likelihood, friction): price vs value",
          "Objection (medium likelihood, friction): need more information",
          "Tension: Desires quality but is constrained by budget"
        ],
