        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I still think about that meal kit. What seemed like a smart, budget-friendly choice ended up making me genuinely sick \u2014 and I swore I'd never let a low price tag fool me again. But here I am, living alone in Chennai on a mid-level salary, constantly doing the math on everything I buy.\n\nI research obsessively before purchasing anything. I'll spend three evenings reading reviews, texting friends who've actually used something, cross-checking prices across platforms. My colleagues' opinions matter more to me than any advertisement \u2014 if someone I trust has vetted it, I'll listen seriously.\n\nThe honest frustration? Quality costs money I don't always have. So I wait, I compare, I hold off until I'm genuinely confident a purchase is worth it. I refuse to compromise on standards, even when my budget is quietly arguing otherwise.",
          "third_person": "Divya Krishnaswamy is a 28-year-old postgraduate professional living alone in Chennai, navigating the careful calculus of early-career financial reality against an uncompromising standard for quality. Her analytical decision style \u2014 reflected in a measured score of 0.32 \u2014 means she rarely acts impulsively, instead methodically mapping options against perceived value before committing to any purchase.\n\nHer behavior is best understood through the lens of a formative experience: a contaminated meal kit that left her deeply distrustful of low-cost food alternatives. This incident didn't simply shift her preferences \u2014 it restructured her entire risk framework. She now treats cheap options as inherently suspect, even when her middle income makes premium choices genuinely difficult to sustain.\n\nRather than resolving this tension independently, Divya characteristically defers to her peer network, using social validation as a quality signal where her own research reaches its limits. She trusts what trusted friends actually use over brand messaging or promotional pricing.\n\nThe result is a consumer who shops slowly, questions discounts, and absorbs peer recommendations deeply \u2014 perpetually negotiating between what she can afford and what she believes she deserves.",
          "display_name": "Divya"
        },
