          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I still think about that capstone project \u2014 the moment everything fell apart because someone cut corners to save money. I swore I'd never let that happen on my watch, professionally or personally. But living alone in Bengaluru on a mid-level salary makes that harder than it sounds.\n\nEvery purchase becomes a negotiation with myself. I want the best version of things \u2014 the laptop that won't lag, the headphones that actually last. But I'm constantly running the numbers, checking if the quality genuinely justifies the price. I don't impulse buy; I ask colleagues, check what my friends from college are using, cross-reference their experiences before I commit.\n\nIt's not indecisiveness \u2014 it's diligence. I've seen what happens when you compromise on quality for convenience. I'd rather wait, save, and buy right the first time.",
          "third_person": "Nikhil Bhat is a 25-year-old postgraduate professional living independently in Bengaluru, navigating the early pressures of career-building on a middle-income salary. His decision-making is fundamentally shaped by a formative academic experience \u2014 a capstone project that collapsed under the weight of budget shortcuts \u2014 which instilled in him a near-instinctive resistance to compromising on quality, even when finances push back.\n\nThis core tension defines much of his consumer behavior. Nikhil does not impulsively pursue the cheapest option; instead, he engages in deliberate, extended evaluation, searching for the intersection between affordability and integrity. He is highly price-sensitive, but price alone never closes the decision \u2014 value does.\n\nWhat accelerates his choices is peer validation. Because he distrusts his own confidence in unfamiliar categories, he anchors heavily on what people within his trusted social circle have already tried and approved. Their experience functions as a quality proxy, reducing his perceived risk.\n\nUltimately, Nikhil moves slowly, asks questions, and waits for social confirmation \u2014 not from indecisiveness, but from a disciplined unwillingness to repeat the mistakes quality shortcuts once cost him.",
          "display_name": "Nikhil"
        },
