          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be low price-sensitive \u2014 you rarely let price dictate your choices, prioritising value and quality over finding the cheapest option. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Wants control but is drawn to delegating decisions to others."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I've been burned before. A consultant team I trusted to deliver a critical project handed me back something half-baked \u2014 polished on the surface, hollow underneath. Since then, I don't fully release the wheel, even when I know I should.\n\nIt's exhausting, honestly. I have the bandwidth to delegate, the team around me, the network to tap \u2014 but something pulls me back to verify everything myself. I'll spend forty minutes cross-checking a recommendation my colleague already researched thoroughly.\n\nPrice rarely stops me. If something is genuinely better, I'll pay for it without much debate. What slows me down is not having enough information to feel certain. I'll ask around \u2014 what are people I respect actually using, actually experiencing \u2014 but then I'll still want to personally validate what I hear before I commit.",
          "third_person": "Rohan Mehta is a 36-year-old Mumbai-based professional whose decision-making is fundamentally shaped by a formative professional betrayal. Following a consultant handover that went wrong, he developed a compulsive need to personally verify outcomes rather than fully trust delegated work \u2014 a pattern that now permeates his consumer behavior as much as his professional life.\n\nDespite self-identifying as his own primary trust anchor, Rohan paradoxically monitors peer behavior closely before committing to a position. This apparent contradiction resolves when understood as a risk-management strategy: peer signals function as pre-screening data rather than genuine social conformity. He is gathering intelligence, not following crowds.\n\nHis analytical orientation (0.34) means he rarely acts on instinct alone, preferring to accumulate information until confidence reaches a personal threshold. Price holds little sway over him; quality is the dominant filter. This reflects both his upper-middle income security and a deep-seated belief that cheap solutions create expensive problems later.\n\nThe central tension in Rohan's decision architecture \u2014 wanting to delegate while being unable to fully relinquish control \u2014 makes him a slow, thorough, and ultimately self-reliant decision-maker who perpetually audits his own conclusions.",
          "display_name": "Rohan"
        },
