          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be low price-sensitive \u2014 you rarely let price dictate your choices, prioritising value and quality over finding the cheapest option. You're most influenced by expert \u2014 you give heavy weight to credentialed experts and official sources when evaluating options. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Wants control but is drawn to delegating decisions to others."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I've learned the hard way that delegating critical decisions without oversight is a gamble I can't afford. During that merger integration \u2014 watching months of work unravel because I trusted others to handle the details \u2014 something shifted in me permanently. Now I review everything significant myself before signing off.\n\nBut I'll be honest: there's a constant pull toward letting go. My calendar is already stretched thin between work and family, and I genuinely want to trust qualified people to carry the load. The tension never fully resolves.\n\nWhat grounds me is gathering enough information first. I'm not chasing the cheapest option \u2014 never have been. I'm looking for quality that holds up under scrutiny, validated by credentialed experts whose reasoning I can actually examine myself. Because ultimately, when something goes wrong, I'm the one accountable. That much the merger taught me clearly.",
          "third_person": "Venkat Subramaniam is a 44-year-old Bengaluru-based professional whose decision-making is fundamentally shaped by a formative professional failure. A merger integration that unraveled under delegated oversight left him with a deep, structural distrust of outcomes he cannot personally verify \u2014 a scar that now manifests as compulsive thoroughness across consequential choices.\n\nHis analytical orientation explains why he consistently seeks more information before committing. This is not indecision; it is a learned defensive posture. He trusts himself as the final arbiter, yet paradoxically feels the pull of delegation \u2014 likely because the cognitive load of controlling every outcome is exhausting for someone managing a demanding career and a nuclear household.\n\nHe gravitates toward credentialed experts not to surrender control, but to enrich the information base he personally scrutinizes. Expert opinion becomes input, never instruction. Price rarely moves him because quality functions as his primary risk-reduction mechanism \u2014 paying more feels safer than regretting a cheaper compromise.\n\nVenkat is, at his core, a man who learned that trust must be earned through evidence, beginning with himself.",
          "display_name": "Venkat"
        },
