          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be medium price-sensitive \u2014 you balance affordability with value, willing to pay more for quality but keeping an eye on the total spend. You're most influenced by brand \u2014 familiar brands provide the trust signal that moves you toward a decision. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I've built a mental shortlist of brands I trust, and I don't deviate from it easily. Living alone in Bengaluru on a single income means every purchase decision carries real weight \u2014 I can't afford to get it wrong and rebuy. During my postgrad, I once trusted a supervisor's methodology recommendation without checking the literature myself, and it cost me three weeks of rework. I don't repeat that mistake. Before I commit to anything, I'm pulling spec sheets, reading teardowns, cross-checking reviews against my own criteria. The tension I live with is this: I know the quality I want, I can usually identify the brand that delivers it, but the price point sometimes forces me to wait or compromise. I'd rather delay than settle. Cutting corners always costs more in the end \u2014 I learned that the hard way.",
          "third_person": "Arjun Menon is a 29-year-old postgraduate professional living alone in Bengaluru, navigating the early stages of a career while managing a middle income on a single-person household budget. His decision-making is fundamentally shaped by a formative academic experience \u2014 a forced methodology overhaul during his thesis \u2014 that instilled a deep distrust of shortcuts and secondhand validation. This backstory explains why he defaults to self-directed research before committing to any purchase, refusing to rely on peer recommendations or promotional claims at face value.\n\nArjun's primary value is quality, yet his budget creates a persistent internal tension that drives much of his consumer behavior. He is not a bargain-hunter, but he monitors total spend carefully, willing to stretch financially only when quality is demonstrably justified. What resolves this tension most reliably is brand familiarity. Recognized brands function as pre-verified trust signals for him, compressing the research burden he would otherwise impose on himself. Crucially, once a brand earns his confidence through personal verification, his loyalty becomes exceptionally strong \u2014 he does not drift toward alternatives without compelling, self-researched justification.",
          "display_name": "Arjun"
        },
