          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I learned my lesson the hard way with that mixer grinder. Bought the cheaper one to save two thousand rupees, and within eight months the motor burned out during my wife's cooking. Replacing it cost more than what I'd originally saved. That stuck with me.\n\nNow, with a toddler at home and a single income carrying three of us, every purchase feels like a negotiation I'm having with myself. I want the best \u2014 I genuinely believe quality is worth paying for. But the EMI commitments don't disappear just because I've convinced myself something is \"worth it.\"\n\nSo I talk to friends first. What are they using? What's held up for them? Their real-world experiences matter more to me than any advertisement. I'm not chasing brands blindly, but when trust is earned, I stay loyal. I just need the price to cooperate.",
          "third_person": "Siddharth Iyer is a 32-year-old postgraduate professional navigating early family life in Hyderabad's competitive urban environment. His decision-making is fundamentally shaped by a formative experience with a faulty mixer grinder \u2014 a low-cost purchase that failed prematurely, teaching him that cutting corners is ultimately more expensive. This \"false economy\" lesson anchors his quality-first orientation, even as his middle-income reality imposes genuine budget constraints.\n\nWhat makes Siddharth analytically interesting is the productive tension between aspiration and limitation. He does not simply want cheap products; he wants the best product his budget can justify. This drives unusually careful price-versus-value calculations before any significant purchase.\n\nHis social decision style explains his reliance on peer networks rather than advertising or expert reviews. Because his family of three amplifies the consequences of poor choices, trust migrates toward people who share his circumstances. Family remains his ultimate trust anchor.\n\nBrand loyalty, once earned, is strong \u2014 because switching carries risk he cannot afford emotionally or financially. Siddharth essentially treats trusted brands as pre-validated quality signals, reducing the cognitive burden of repeated deliberation.",
          "display_name": "Siddharth"
        },
