          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I still remember the week my wife fell sick after we used that cheap cooking oil \u2014 the one I bought because it was fifty rupees less. That incident changed how I think about every single thing I bring into this home. Now I read every label, check every brand, ask around in my colony WhatsApp group before I commit to anything.\n\nBut Delhi life with a three-year-old and one salary doesn't give you much room. I want the best for my family \u2014 genuinely good products, not just packaging that looks premium. So I calculate. I wait for the right deal. I ask colleagues what they're using. I won't compromise on quality, but I also can't ignore what this month's budget looks like. That tension lives with me daily.",
          "third_person": "Sameer Khan is a 30-year-old Delhi-based professional navigating the complicated intersection of aspiration and financial reality. Having witnessed firsthand the consequences of compromised product quality through a formative adulteration incident, he developed a meticulous, scrutiny-driven approach to household purchases that goes well beyond typical consumer caution. He reads ingredient labels, researches brand reputations, and cross-references peer experiences before committing to anything significant.\n\nHis analytical decision style explains why he rarely acts impulsively \u2014 every purchase is mentally stress-tested against both quality standards and budget constraints. This creates a persistent internal tension: he genuinely believes cheaper alternatives carry hidden costs, yet his middle income and nuclear household responsibilities demand fiscal discipline.\n\nPeer influence operates as his primary validation mechanism, essentially a social quality filter that reduces his perceived risk. If trusted people in his circle endorse something, it simultaneously confirms quality and justifies the price. His brand loyalty is therefore not passive habit but earned trust \u2014 a hard-won psychological contract. For Sameer, spending more on something reliable is not extravagance; it is protection.",
          "display_name": "Sameer"
        },
