    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-003",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still think about that laptop I bought in my second year at Anna University \u2014 the one that died three months in because I chose the cheaper option. Lost assignments, repair costs, the whole nightmare. That lesson stuck with me hard.\n\nNow I'm living alone in Chennai on a mid-level salary, and every significant purchase feels like a calculation. I want the good stuff \u2014 I genuinely believe quality pays for itself over time \u2014 but my budget doesn't always agree with my principles. So I spend hours on 91mobiles threads, Reddit, YouTube reviews, asking colleagues what they actually use and regret. I trust real people over brand promises.\n\nI'm not impulsive. I'll wait, compare, revisit. But once the community consensus aligns with the value I'm seeing, I commit. Cutting corners burned me once. I won't let it happen again.",
        "third_person": "Karthik Rajan is a 27-year-old postgraduate professional living alone in Chennai, navigating early career demands on a middle income. His consumer behavior is fundamentally shaped by a formative experience \u2014 a defective laptop purchase during his Anna University years that taught him, concretely, that cheap often costs more over time. This single incident recalibrated his entire decision-making framework around quality as a non-negotiable primary value, even when his tight metro rental and student loan repayments resist it.\n\nWhat makes Karthik analytically distinctive is the deliberate tension he manages rather than resolves. He systematically researches options on platforms like 91mobiles, Flipkart reviews, and tech forums, leaning heavily on peer consensus and colleague recommendations as his most trusted signal \u2014 essentially outsourcing risk assessment to collective experience rather than brand authority. His switching behavior is measured and slow, reflecting a risk-averse temperament that demands sufficient evidence before committing. Price-to-value ratio is his central evaluative lens."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Anna University (postgraduate institution)",
        "91mobiles (India-specific tech review platform)",
        "Flipkart reviews (India-specific e-commerce review ecosystem)",
        "Chennai metro rental context (regional income-expense specificity)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "postgrad studies",
          "replacement": "postgrad studies at Anna University",
          "attribute_source": "location.region + education.level"
        },
        {
          "original": "online reviews and community consensus",
          "replacement": "91mobiles threads, Reddit, Flipkart reviews, and colleague recommendations",
          "attribute_source": "location.country + behavioral_summary.community_influence"
        },
        {
          "original": "forums, Reddit threads, YouTube reviews",
          "replacement": "91mobiles threads, tech forums, YouTube reviews, and Flipkart community posts",
          "attribute_source": "location.country + income.metro_context"
        }
      ],
      "validation_status": {
        "cr1_isolation": "pass",
        "cr2_stereotype_audit": "not_run",
        "cr3_cultural_realism": "not_run",
        "cr4_persona_fidelity": "not_run"
      },
      "skip_reason": null
    },
    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-010",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still think about that meal kit from Freshmenu. What seemed like a smart, budget-friendly choice ended up making me genuinely sick \u2014 and I swore I'd never let a low price tag fool me again. But here I am, living alone in Chennai on a mid-level salary, constantly doing the math on everything I buy.\n\nI research obsessively before purchasing anything. I'll spend three evenings reading reviews on Swantest or Amazon, texting friends who've actually used something, cross-checking prices across BigBasket and Spencer's. My colleagues' opinions matter more to me than any advertisement \u2014 if someone I trust has vetted it, I'll listen seriously.\n\nThe honest frustration? Quality costs money I don't always have. So I wait, I compare, I hold off until I'm genuinely confident a purchase is worth it. I refuse to compromise on standards, even when my budget is quietly arguing otherwise.",
        "third_person": "Divya Krishnaswamy is a 28-year-old postgraduate professional living alone in Chennai, navigating the careful calculus of early-career financial reality against an uncompromising standard for quality. Her analytical decision style \u2014 reflected in a measured score of 0.32 \u2014 means she rarely acts impulsively, instead methodically mapping options across BigBasket, Spencer's, and D-Mart before committing to any purchase.\n\nHer behavior is best understood through a formative experience: contaminated food from a budget meal delivery service that left her deeply distrustful of low-cost food alternatives. This incident didn't simply shift her preferences \u2014 it restructured her entire risk framework, much like watching her senior colleague's crypto losses reinforced her reliance on HDFC fixed deposits over aggressive instruments.\n\nRather than resolving this tension independently, Divya characteristically defers to her peer network, using social validation as a quality signal where her own research reaches its limits. She trusts what trusted friends actually use over brand messaging or promotional pricing. The result is a consumer who shops slowly, questions discounts, and absorbs peer recommendations deeply \u2014 perpetually negotiating between what she can afford and what she believes she deserves."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Freshmenu (regional meal kit service, Chennai-relevant)",
        "BigBasket (major grocery delivery platform, metro Chennai context)",
        "Spencer's (retail chain present in Chennai)",
        "D-Mart (accessible retail chain, middle-income verification)",
        "Swantest (product review platform, peer-validation channel)",
        "HDFC fixed deposits (conservative financial instrument, matches risk profile)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "a meal kit subscription",
          "replacement": "Freshmenu",
          "attribute_source": "location.city, age at incident (25), income_bracket (middle)"
        },
        {
