    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-013",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still think about that capstone project \u2014 the moment everything fell apart because someone cut corners to save money. I swore I'd never let that happen on my watch, professionally or personally. But living alone in Bengaluru on a mid-level salary makes that harder than it sounds.\n\nEvery purchase becomes a negotiation with myself. I want the best version of things \u2014 the laptop that won't lag, the headphones that actually last. But I'm constantly running the numbers, checking Flipkart reviews and what my friends from college are using on their setups, cross-referencing their experiences before I commit. I researched my Koramangala flat the same way \u2014 paid 15% extra because cheaper options had plumbing issues confirmed by tenant feedback.\n\nIt's not indecisiveness \u2014 it's diligence. I've seen what happens when you compromise on quality for convenience. I'd rather wait, save, and buy right the first time.",
        "third_person": "Nikhil Bhat is a 25-year-old postgraduate professional living independently in Koramangala, Bengaluru, navigating the early pressures of career-building on a middle-income salary. His decision-making is fundamentally shaped by a formative academic experience \u2014 a capstone project that collapsed under the weight of budget shortcuts \u2014 which instilled in him a near-instinctive resistance to compromising on quality, even when finances push back.\n\nThis core tension defines much of his consumer behavior. Nikhil does not impulsively pursue the cheapest option; instead, he engages in deliberate, extended evaluation on platforms like Flipkart and Amazon, searching for the intersection between affordability and integrity. He is highly price-sensitive, but price alone never closes the decision \u2014 value does. What accelerates his choices is peer validation from college circles and Bengaluru colleagues. Their experience functions as a quality proxy, reducing his perceived risk.\n\nUltimately, Nikhil moves slowly, asks questions, and waits for social confirmation \u2014 not from indecisiveness, but from disciplined unwillingness to repeat the mistakes quality shortcuts once cost him."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Flipkart reviews",
        "Amazon",
        "Koramangala (specific Bengaluru locality)",
        "tenant feedback systems (Indian rental verification practice)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "check what my friends from college are using",
          "replacement": "checking Flipkart reviews and what my friends from college are using on their setups",
          "attribute_source": "location.city, income_bracket (metro middle-income digital native)"
        },
        {
          "original": "living alone in Bengaluru",
          "replacement": "living independently in Koramangala, Bengaluru",
          "attribute_source": "location.city, life_story (age 24 apartment decision)"
        },
        {
          "original": "cross-reference their experiences",
          "replacement": "cross-referencing Flipkart reviews and their experiences",
          "attribute_source": "location.city, behavioral_summary (peer influence + digital verification)"
        }
      ],
      "validation_status": {
        "cr1_isolation": "pass",
        "cr2_stereotype_audit": "not_run",
        "cr3_cultural_realism": "not_run",
