    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-009",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've been burned before. A consultant team I trusted to deliver a critical project handed me back something half-baked \u2014 polished on the surface, hollow underneath. Since then, I don't fully release the wheel, even when I know I should.\n\nIt's exhausting, honestly. I have the bandwidth to delegate, the team around me, the network to tap \u2014 but something pulls me back to verify everything myself. I'll spend forty minutes cross-checking a recommendation my colleague already researched thoroughly.\n\nPrice rarely stops me. If something is genuinely better, I'll pay for it without much debate. What slows me down is not having enough information to feel certain. I'll ask around \u2014 what are people I respect at NAAREE or through my B-school network actually using, actually experiencing \u2014 but then I'll still want to personally validate what I hear before I commit.",
        "third_person": "Rohan Mehta is a 36-year-old Mumbai-based professional whose decision-making is fundamentally shaped by a formative professional betrayal. Following a consultant handover that went wrong, he developed a compulsive need to personally verify outcomes rather than fully trust delegated work \u2014 a pattern that now permeates his consumer behavior as much as his professional life.\n\nDespite self-identifying as his own primary trust anchor, Rohan paradoxically monitors peer behavior closely before committing to a position \u2014 whether through his JBIMS alumni circles or professional networks in Bandra-Kurla. This apparent contradiction resolves when understood as a risk-management strategy: peer signals function as pre-screening data rather than genuine social conformity. He is gathering intelligence, not following crowds.\n\nHis analytical orientation means he rarely acts on instinct alone, preferring to accumulate information until confidence reaches a personal threshold. Price holds little sway over him; quality is the dominant filter. This reflects both his upper-middle income security and a deep-seated belief that cheap solutions create expensive problems later. The central tension in Rohan's decision architecture \u2014 wanting to delegate while being unable to fully relinquish control \u2014 makes him a slow, thorough, and ultimately self-reliant decision-maker who perpetually audits his own conclusions."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "NAAREE (peer/professional network marker for upper-middle Mumbai)",
        "JBIMS alumni circles (educational institution and social network)",
        "Bandra-Kurla (Mumbai business district, location-specific contextual anchor)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "people I respect",
          "replacement": "people I respect at NAAREE or through my B-school network",
          "attribute_source": "location.city + education.postgraduate"
        },
        {
          "original": "generic peer reference",
          "replacement": "JBIMS alumni circles or professional networks in Bandra-Kurla",
          "attribute_source": "location.city + life_story.age_24"
        }
      ],
      "validation_status": {
        "cr1_isolation": "pass",
        "cr2_stereotype_audit": "not_run",
        "cr3_cultural_realism": "not_run",
        "cr4_persona_fidelity": "not_run"
      },
      "skip_reason": null
    },
    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-007",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've learned the hard way that delegating critical decisions without oversight is a gamble I can't afford. During that merger integration \u2014 watching months of work unravel because I trusted others to handle the details \u2014 something shifted in me permanently. Now I review everything significant myself before signing off.\n\nBut I'll be honest: there's a constant pull toward letting go. My calendar is already stretched thin between work and family, and I genuinely want to trust qualified people to carry the load. The tension never fully resolves.\n\nWhat grounds me is gathering enough information first. I'm not chasing the cheapest option \u2014 never have been. I'm looking for quality that holds up under scrutiny, validated by credentialed experts whose reasoning I can actually examine myself. When I evaluated my Jayanagar property, I cross-checked construction specs against CREDAI standards and cardiologist recommendations against PubMed literature. Because ultimately, when something goes wrong, I'm the one accountable. That much the merger taught me clearly.",
        "third_person": "Venkat Subramaniam is a 44-year-old Bengaluru-based IT professional whose decision-making is fundamentally shaped by a formative merger integration failure \u2014 an unraveled project under delegated oversight that left him with deep structural distrust of outcomes he cannot personally verify. This scar now manifests as compulsive thoroughness across consequential choices, whether reviewing vendor deliverables at work or cross-checking cardiologist recommendations against peer-reviewed literature during his father's cardiac event.\n\nHis analytical orientation explains why he consistently seeks more information before committing\u2014a learned defensive posture, not indecision. He trusts himself as the final arbiter, yet feels the paradoxical pull of delegation, likely because the cognitive load of controlling every outcome is exhausting for someone managing demanding career responsibilities and a nuclear household in Bengaluru's upper-middle professional ecosystem.\n\nHe gravitates toward credentialed experts not to surrender control, but to enrich the information base he personally scrutinizes. Expert opinion becomes input, never instruction. Price rarely moves him; his 3BHK negotiation and property research exemplify how quality functions as his primary risk-reduction mechanism. Venkat is, at his core, a man who learned that trust must be earned through evidence, beginning with himself."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "CREDAI standards (Confederation of Real Estate Development Associations \u2014 authoritative construction benchmark in India)",
        "PubMed literature (credentialed expert verification method, aligns with his post-merger analytical discipline)",
        "Jayanagar property (specific Bengaluru locality reference from life story)",
        "cardiologist recommendations cross-check (traces to age 41 Chennai episode)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "generic expert validation reference",
          "replacement": "credentialed experts whose reasoning I can actually examine myself. When I evaluated my Jayanagar property, I cross-checked construction specs against CREDAI standards and cardiologist recommendations against PubMed literature.",
          "attribute_source": "location.city + life_stories (property purchase, father's MI episode)"
        },
        {
          "original": "something goes wrong",
          "replacement": "something goes wrong \u2014 like that merger integration, or like when my father's cardiac event required me to personally cross-check every prescription",
          "attribute_source": "life_stories (age 34 merger, age 41 MI coordination)"
        }
      ],
      "validation_status": {
        "cr1_isolation": "pass",
        "cr2_stereotype_audit": "not_run",
        "cr3_cultural_realism": "not_run",
        "cr4_persona_fidelity": "not_run"
