    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-001",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've built a mental shortlist of brands I trust \u2014 Lenovo, Decathlon, Croma \u2014 and I don't deviate from it easily. Living alone in Bengaluru on a single income means every purchase decision carries real weight \u2014 I can't afford to get it wrong and rebuy. During my postgrad, I once trusted a supervisor's methodology recommendation without checking the literature myself, and it cost me three weeks of rework. I don't repeat that mistake. Before I commit to anything, I'm pulling spec sheets, reading 91mobiles teardowns and tech forums, cross-checking reviews against my own criteria. The tension I live with is this: I know the quality I want, I can usually identify the brand that delivers it, but the price point sometimes forces me to wait or compromise. I'd rather delay than settle. Cutting corners always costs more in the end \u2014 I learned that the hard way.",
        "third_person": "Arjun Menon is a 29-year-old postgraduate professional living alone in Bengaluru, navigating the early stages of a career while managing a middle income on a single-person household budget. His decision-making is fundamentally shaped by a formative academic experience \u2014 a forced methodology overhaul during his thesis \u2014 that instilled a deep distrust of shortcuts and secondhand validation. This backstory explains why he defaults to self-directed research on tech review platforms and Flipkart's detailed spec comparisons before committing to any purchase, refusing to rely on peer recommendations or promotional claims at face value.\n\nArjun's primary value is quality, yet his budget creates a persistent internal tension that drives much of his consumer behavior. He is not a bargain-hunter, but he monitors total spend carefully through Bangalore's mid-tier retail ecosystem (Croma, Decathlon, Amazon Fresh), willing to stretch financially only when quality is demonstrably justified. What resolves this tension most reliably is brand familiarity. Recognized brands function as pre-verified trust signals for him, compressing the research burden he would otherwise impose on himself. Crucially, once a brand earns his confidence through personal verification, his loyalty becomes exceptionally strong \u2014 he does not drift toward alternatives without compelling, self-researched justification."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Lenovo (trusted tech brand in India)",
        "Decathlon (affordable durability retail chain across metros)",
        "Croma (electronics retailer aligned with middle-income, quality-conscious purchasing)",
        "91mobiles (India-specific tech review and teardown platform)",
        "Flipkart (India's dominant e-commerce platform for spec comparison)",
        "Amazon Fresh (Bengaluru-specific retail channel)",
        "tech forums (implicit reference to Indian tech communities)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "a supermarket",
          "replacement": "Bangalore's mid-tier retail ecosystem (Croma, Decathlon, Amazon Fresh)",
          "attribute_source": "location.city + income_bracket + education (postgraduate + full-time employment supports mid-tier retail access)"
        },
        {
          "original": "reading teardowns, cross-checking reviews",
          "replacement": "reading 91mobiles teardowns and tech forums, cross-checking reviews",
          "attribute_source": "location.city (Bengaluru tech hub) + education (postgraduate) + employment (full-time, early-career in likely tech sector)"
        }
      ],
      "validation_status": {
        "cr1_isolation": "pass",
        "cr2_stereotype_audit": "not_run",
        "cr3_cultural_realism": "not_run",
        "cr4_persona_fidelity": "not_run"
      },
      "skip_reason": null
    },
    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-018",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've spent thirty years building expertise in my field, and I've learned one hard truth: trusting blindly costs you more than any premium product ever will. That misdiagnosed report from Apollo \u2014 where three different specialists missed something I eventually caught myself by reading the actual pathology notes \u2014 rewired something fundamental in me. I don't outsource my judgment anymore. Not to doctors, not to family, certainly not to salespeople.\n\nYet I catch myself constantly tempted to just let someone else decide. I'm tired. I'm busy. And sometimes delegating feels like relief.\n\nBut I resist it. When I'm evaluating something significant \u2014 a healthcare plan, a financial product, a home renovation \u2014 I gather everything. I read credentials, cross-reference sources, verify claims independently. Price barely enters my thinking. What I'm buying is certainty, and certainty has no discount season.",
        "third_person": "Usha Srinivasan, a 52-year-old postgraduate-educated professional based in Chennai, navigates her late-career decisions through a carefully constructed lens of self-reliance. A formative experience at Apollo Chennai with a misdiagnosed lab report fundamentally rewired her relationship with expertise and delegation, producing a researcher who trusts herself above all others \u2014 even when she privately wishes she could hand decisions off to someone more knowledgeable.\n\nThis internal contradiction is central to understanding her behavior. She gravitates toward credentialed experts and official sources not to surrender judgment, but to gather ammunition for her own verification process. She reads medical journals, cross-references ICICI Prudential and HDFC fund prospectuses, and interrogates information before committing. Price rarely moves her; quality and demonstrable value are her currencies.\n\nHer analytical style \u2014 though moderate rather than dominant \u2014 means she accumulates information systematically, often stalling decisions while seeking completeness. Brand loyalty functions as a cognitive shortcut she permits herself only after trust has been independently established. Once earned through rigorous personal testing, that loyalty remains durable."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Apollo Chennai (referencing healthcare institution from life story)",
        "ICICI Prudential (upper-middle income financial product, Chennai metro context)",
        "HDFC (conservative debt fund provider, matches her 2015 flood-era investment behavior)",
        "Medical journals (specific to her cardiology verification behavior)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "a healthcare plan, a financial product",
          "replacement": "an Apollo health insurance plan, ICICI Prudential fund prospectuses",
          "attribute_source": "location.city + income_bracket + life_story.financial_conservatism"
        },
