      "persona_id": "pg-pg-005",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I learned my lesson the hard way with that mixer grinder. Bought the cheaper one to save two thousand rupees, and within eight months the motor burned out during my wife's cooking. Replacing it cost more than what I'd originally saved. That stuck with me.\n\nNow, with a toddler at home and a single income carrying three of us, every purchase feels like a negotiation I'm having with myself. I want the best \u2014 I genuinely believe quality is worth paying for. But the EMI commitments don't disappear just because I've convinced myself something is \"worth it.\"\n\nSo I talk to friends first. What are they using at home? What's held up for them through Hyderabad's heat and power cuts? Their real-world experiences matter more to me than any advertisement. I'm not chasing brands blindly, but when trust is earned \u2014 whether it's Prestige or Philips \u2014 I stay loyal. I just need the price to cooperate.",
        "third_person": "Siddharth Iyer is a 32-year-old postgraduate professional navigating early family life in Hyderabad's competitive urban environment, where middle-income households balance aspiration against infrastructure realities like erratic power supply. His decision-making is fundamentally shaped by a formative experience with a faulty mixer grinder \u2014 a low-cost purchase that failed prematurely, teaching him that cutting corners is ultimately more expensive. This \"false economy\" lesson anchors his quality-first orientation, even as his budget constraints are genuine.\n\nWhat makes Siddharth analytically interesting is the productive tension between aspiration and limitation. He does not simply want cheap products; he wants the best product his budget can justify. This drives unusually careful price-versus-value calculations before any significant purchase.\n\nHis social decision style explains his reliance on peer networks and family counsel rather than advertising. Because his household of three amplifies the consequences of poor choices \u2014 as his daughter's formula incident reinforced \u2014 trust migrates toward people who share his circumstances and understand Hyderabad's specific living conditions. Brand loyalty, once earned through peer validation, is strong and durable."
      },
