      "persona_id": "pg-pg-015",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still remember the week my wife fell sick after we used that cheap cooking oil \u2014 the one I bought because it was fifty rupees less. That incident changed how I think about every single thing I bring into this home. Now I read every label, check every brand, ask around in my colony WhatsApp group before I commit to anything. I've learned to trust consumer forums like IndiaStack before making decisions.\n\nBut Delhi life with a three-year-old and one salary doesn't give you much room. I want the best for my family \u2014 genuinely good products, not just packaging that looks premium. So I calculate. I wait for the right deal at D-Mart or Big Basket. I ask colleagues what they're using. I won't compromise on quality, but I also can't ignore what this month's budget looks like. That tension lives with me daily.",
        "third_person": "Sameer Khan is a 30-year-old Delhi-based professional navigating the complicated intersection of aspiration and financial reality. Having witnessed firsthand the consequences of compromised product quality through a formative adultification incident, he developed a meticulous, scrutiny-driven approach to household purchases that goes well beyond typical consumer caution. He reads ingredient labels, researches brand reputations on consumer forums, and cross-references peer experiences in his colony WhatsApp groups before committing to anything significant.\n\nHis analytical decision style explains why he rarely acts impulsively \u2014 every purchase is mentally stress-tested against both quality standards and budget constraints. This creates a persistent internal tension: he genuinely believes cheaper alternatives carry hidden costs, yet his middle income and nuclear household responsibilities demand fiscal discipline. Peer influence operates as his primary validation mechanism through trusted circles and workplace networks. His brand loyalty is therefore not passive habit but earned trust \u2014 a hard-won psychological contract forged through careful observation and shared community feedback."
